Datasets

For this activity we will be using the blue_jays, BA_degrees, dow_jones_industrial and cdc data set that should be located in your /data subdirectory. An explanation of the variables in the data set are provided below in their respective Exercises.

# Load package(s)
library(tidyverse)

# Load rda data files
load("data/BA_degrees.rda")

Exercise 1

Weâll be using data from the blue_jays.rda dataset to answer the following questions and construct the following plots.

Below is a description of the variables contained in the dataset.

  • BirdID - ID tag for bird
  • KnownSex - Sex coded as F or M
  • BillDepth - Thickness of the bill measured at the nostril (in mm)
  • BillWidth - Width of the bill (in mm)
  • BillLength - Length of the bill (in mm)
  • Head - Distance from tip of bill to back of head (in mm)
  • Mass - Body mass (in grams)
  • Skull - Distance from base of bill to back of skull (in mm)
  • Sex - Sex coded as 0 = female or 1 = male


Question 1.1

Three commonly used aesthetics for enhancing a graphic are color, size, and shape. We can either map variables or fixed values to these.

In the blue_jays dataset which variables would be appropriate to map to the size aesthetic? The shape aesthetic? The color aesthetic?

Solution
  • size: BillDepth, BillWidth, BillLength, Head, Mass, and Skull would be the most appropriate to map to size because they are quantitative/continuous variables by nature.
  • shape: KnownSex would be most appropriate to map to shape because it is ideal for categorical and/or nominal data. There are only two possible values for KnownSex making it easy to distinguish between two possible shapes. Sex is interpreted as continuous and thus canât be mapped to shape.
  • color: KnownSex and Sex are the most appropriate to be mapped to color because color mainly deals with categorical data. As the 2nd plot in this question shows, the legend created by mapping Sex to color creates a confusing legend but the plot itself is correct.


Plot 1

Construct a scatterplots of Head by Mass with the following criteria:

  • color aesthetic set to Northwestern purple (#4E2A84)
  • shape aesthetic set a solid/filled triangle
  • size aesthetic set to 2.
Solution 
ggplot(data=blue_jays, aes(x=Mass, y=Head)) + 
  geom_point(color="#4E2A84", shape = 17, size = 2) +
  labs(x="Mass (g)", y="Head (mm)")


Plot 2

Construct a scatterplot of Head by Mass with the following criteria:

  • size aesthetic to 2.
  • Either Sex or KnownSex mapped to the color aesthetic.
Solution 
ggplot(data=blue_jays, aes(x=Mass, y=Head, color=KnownSex)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(x="Mass (g)", y="Head (mm)",color = "Sex")


Question 1.2

Was it more appropriate to map Sex or KnownSex to the color aesthetic in Plot 2 and why?

Solution

KnownSex was the more appropriate variable to choose in this scenario. While using either variable produces a âcorrectâ plot, the Sex variable is being treated as continuous and thus the legend that is produced serves as a color gradient, which can be confusing to read and interpret when there are only two possible outcomes.


Question 1.3

Consider the color aesthetic in Plot 1 and Plot 2 above. Explain why these two usages of the color aesthetic are meaningfully different.

Solution

In the first plot,color is not really used as an aesthetic. No variables are mapped onto to color and it is not being used to represent a variable in the data. In the second plot, color helps distinguish between the âMâ and âFâ groups from the KnownSex variable. In the second plot, color adds an additional layer of analysis in that we can analyze the relationship between Head and Mass while accounting for differences in the sex blue jays. The first plot simply plots the relationship between Head and Mass with no additional context, as color in this instance provides no additional information.


Exercise 2

Weâll be using data from the BA_degrees.rda which is already in the /data subdirectory in our data_vis_labs project. Below is a description of the variables contained in the dataset.

BA_degrees.rda

  • field - field of study
  • year_str - academic year (e.g.Â 1970-71)
  • year - closing year of academic year
  • count - number of degrees conferred within a field for the year
  • perc - fieldâs percentage of degrees conferred for the year
# Wrangling for plotting
ba_data <- BA_degrees %>%
  # mean % per field
  group_by(field) %>%
  mutate(mean_perc = mean(perc)) %>%
  # Only fields with mean >= 5%
  filter(mean_perc >= 0.05) %>%
  # Organizing for plotting
  arrange(desc(mean_perc), year) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(field = fct_inorder(field))


Using the ba_data dataset derived from BA_degrees, recreate the following graphics as precisely as possible.

Plot 1

Solution 
ggplot(data=ba_data, aes(x=year, y=perc)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~field) +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Proportion of degrees")


Plot 2

Hints:

  • Transparency is 0.5
  • Color used is"red"
Solution 
ggplot(data=ba_data, aes(x=year, y=perc)) + 
  geom_area(alpha=0.5, fill="red") +
  geom_line(color="red") +
  facet_wrap(~field) + 
  xlab("Year") + 
  ylab("Proportion of degrees")


Plot 3

Solution 
ggplot(data=ba_data, aes(x=year, y=perc, color=field)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x="Year", y="Proportion of degrees",color = "Field")


Exercise 3

Using the dow_jones_industrial dataset, track the Dow Jones Industrial Average at close each day during 2009. Recreate the following graphics as precisely as possible.

# Only keep observations within 2009 range
djia_date_range <- dow_jones_industrial %>%
  filter(
    date >= ymd("2009/01/01") & date < ymd("2010/01/01")
    )


Plot 1

Hints:

  • colors: âpurpleâ, âredâ, âgreenâ
  • Wiggliness for loess is 0.3
Solution 
ggplot(djia_date_range, aes(x=date, y=close)) +
  geom_line(color="purple") +
  geom_smooth(span = 0.3, color="green", fill="red") +
  labs(x= NULL, y="Dow Jones Industrial Average")


Plot 2

There are many different smoothing methods in statistics. By default geom_smooth() uses loess.

Another extremely popular smoothing method in statistics is the use of splines. A spline function is a curve constructed from polynomial segments that are subject to conditions or continuity at their joints. Generally, a difficulty is you need to determine the number of knots, however this method is popular in predictive models.

Add a natural cubic spline smoother with df = 6.

Hints:

  • need the splines package
  • use method "lm"
  • y ~ ns(x, 6)
Solution 
ggplot(djia_date_range, aes(x=date, y=close)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", formula=y~splines::ns(x,6), span=0.3, se=FALSE) +
  labs(x= NULL, y="Dow Jones Industrial Average")


Exercise 4

Weâll be using the BRFSS (Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System) survey collected annually by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The data can be found in the provided cdc.txt file â place this file in your /data subdirectory. The dataset contains 20,000 complete observations/records of 9 variables/fields, described below.

  • genhlth - How would you rate your general health? (excellent, very good, good, fair, poor)
  • exerany - Have you exercised in the past month? (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • hlthplan - Do you have some form of health coverage? (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • smoke100 - Have you smoked at least 100 cigarettes in your life time? (1 = yes, 0 = no)
  • height - height in inches
  • weight - weight in pounds
  • wtdesire - weight desired in pounds
  • age - in years
  • gender - m for males and f for females


Using the cdc dataset, we want to visualize the distribution between weight and gender based on general health. Recreate the Plot 1 and Plot 2 which represent 2 attempts at this.


Plot 1

Hints:

  • Transparency is 0.2
  • Horizontal axis should have lower limit of 50 and upper limit of 400
Solution 
ggplot(cdc, aes(x=weight, fill=genhlth, color=genhlth)) +
  geom_density(alpha=0.2) +
  facet_wrap(~gender) +
  xlim(50, 400)


Plot 2

Hints:

  • Transparency is 0.4
Solution 
ggplot(cdc, aes(x=gender, y=weight, fill=gender)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha=0.4) +
  facet_wrap(~genhlth, nrow=1)


Plot 3

Choose one more way to visualize the distribution of weight based on gender and general health. (Many ways to do this).

Requirements:

  • The geom layer cannot be geom_boxplot() or geom_density()
  • Appropriately label the x- and y- axis
  • Add a title
Solution 
ggplot(cdc, aes(x=gender, y=weight, fill=gender)) +
  geom_violin(alpha=0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~genhlth, nrow=1) +
  labs(x="Gender", y="Weight", fill="Gender", title="Distribution of Weight by Gender and General Health")


Question 4.1

Compare and contrast the different ways to visualize a distribution. In other words, when might you use a histogram vs density vs boxplot? Which did you find the most useful in interpreting the plots above?

Solution

In terms of getting a specific understanding of the distributions of weight by genhlth, density plots have an advantage in this regard. By looking at plot 1, I get can get an understanding of skew and modality. However, especially when the plots are overlaid each other, the plot is a bit hard to read and interpreting concrete differences between the distributions is a bit difficult.

For plot 2, using a boxplot allowed me to clearly see gender differences in weight at all levels of health, but I lose a lot of nuance in the process. With this plot, I donât gain an understanding of the shape of each distribution as well as modality and skew. In this way, density plots and boxplots are complementary to each other in this way.

I would probably choose to use a histogram when a distribution is unimodal and I have an understanding of appropriate bin widths. Bin widths can control the appearance of a distribution.

In this case, I found the side-by-side boxplots to be the most informative about the gender differences in weight by health level. In reality, I would use a combination of density and boxplots to get a more complete understanding. In plot 3, I used a violin plot that combines the specificity of density plots and the distribution differences communicated by the boxplots.


Exercise 5

Using the cdc dataset, construct this plot in two ways. Once using geom_bar() and once using the geom_col(). May need to do some data wrangling for one of these.

Solution 
#plot 1: geom_bar()
ggplot(data=cdc, mapping=aes(x=genhlth)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x="General Health", y="Count")

#plot 2: geom_col()
cdc %>% 
  count(genhlth) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=genhlth, y=n)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x="General Health", y="Count")
